places.generalDescription: Setur Netsel Marmaris Marina is a stunning and popular attraction in Marmaris. The marina is surrounded by picturesque mountains, offering a beautiful setting for leisurely walks along the esplanade. Colorful boats with Turkish flags line the clear blue waters, creating a charming atmosphere. The walkways are adorned with flower beds, fountains, and sculptures, while an array of bars, restaurants, and shops provide ample entertainment options.

sources.snippet: No self-respecting 21st-century resort could be without an upscale marina, but the harbour in Marmaris is all the more alluring against the castle and hills of the Marmaris National Park. The quays and jetties are paved and you can go on a stroll to check out the forest of masts, the superyachts and the rugged topography around the bay. The main quay has a line of cafes, boutiques and restaurants, which continues along the west bank of the river and then along the action-packed Bar Street, which we‚Äôll come to later.

places.generalDescription: Marmaris Castle and Archeology Museum is a must-visit destination for history enthusiasts. Situated on the site of the ancient Marmaris Castle, this 16th-century structure offers breathtaking views and houses a fascinating museum. The castle has a rich history, believed to have been initially built by the Ionians in 1044 BC and later expanded during Suleyman the Magnificent's reign in 1522.

sources.snippet: The castle hosts small but well-organised Marmaris Museum, which exhibits amphorae, tombstones, figurines, oil lamps and other finds from surrounding archaeological sites, including from Knidos and Dat√ßa. Saunter along the castle's walls and ramparts and gaze down on the bustling marina. There are excellent information boards in English and Turkish.

sources.snippet: The history of the majestic Marmaris Castle dates back to over 5000 years ago, when it was believed to have been built by the longest-reigning Sultan of the Ottoman Empire - S√ºleyman the Magnificent. According to historians and ancient records, the castle was built upon the orders of S√ºleyman the Magnificent to serve as an assembly point and military base during his expedition to Rhodes. The castle also played a role during the First World War and was inhabited by locals, with a total of 18 residences up until 1979.

Although it‚Äôs not for sure when Marmaris was founded, but within the sixth century BC the location was called Physkos (Ancient Greek: Œ¶œçœÉŒ∫ŒøœÇ) and regarded a part of Caria. Marmaris Castle and town was dominated by Egyptians, Assyrians, Ionians and Dorian turn. The Dorians divided the Carian province into nine colony cities, such as Halicarnassos and Knidos, then Marmaris became an energetic commerce centre for peninsula and led to a rise in handicrafts and maritime trade.

sources.snippet: Marmaris Castle is one of the city‚Äôs most amazing historical places, a tourist destination for thousands of visitors every year. It has a medium-size yard, surrounded by walls from all sides, with a small amphitheatre and remains of broken statues and clay pots that date back to early ages.

sources.snippet: This town was fortified as long ago as 3000 BCE, but the origins of the castle on the little peninsula between the main beach and marina are 16th-century. Marmaris Castle was reworked at this time by Suleiman the Magnificent (1494-1566) during his Rhodes campaign. That building took heavy damage from French warships in the First World War and came through a ten-year restoration in the 1980s.
